ptions":["HCV antibody testing is used to confirm active infection","HCV RNA testing is used for initial screening","Liver enzymes become elevated within 1-2 weeks of infection","HCV RNA becomes detectable 1-2 weeks after infection","HCV antibodies become detectable within 48 hours of infection"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of HCV infection follows a specific sequence:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHCV antibody testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used for initial screening, not confirmation, as antibodies can persist after cleared infection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHCV RNA testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to confirm active infection, not for screening\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E typically become elevated 4-12 weeks after infection, not 1-2 weeks\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHCV RNA\u003C/strong\u003E becomes detectable in blood 1-2 weeks after infection using nucleic acid testing\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHCV antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E typically take 8-11 weeks to become detectable\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA positive antibody test should always be followed by RNA testing to confirm active infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hepatitis C virus (HCV) antibodies are used for screening, while HCV RNA testing confirms active infection","HCV RNA becomes detectable within 1-2 weeks of infection","Liver function tests typically become elevated 4-12 weeks after infection"],"references":["Mehta P, Grant LM, Reddivari AKR. Viral Hepatitis. 2024 Mar 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119436","Lok AS, Pawlotsky JM. Viral hepatitis at a crossroad. Gastroenterology. 2012 May;142(6):1261-3. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2012.03.007. PMID: 22537431","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Scienc","Song JE, Kim DY. Diagnosis of hepatitis B. Ann Transl Med. 2016 Sep;4(18):338. doi: 10.21037/atm.2016.09.11. PMID: 27761442; PMCID: PMC5066055"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53360"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15363"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53360"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T17:57:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T17:58:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8054"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67895"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount"